## ⚠ Step 0 — DO THIS FIRST, BEFORE ANY OTHER COMMAND

The cleanroom container ships the reference binary at
`{{ workspace_dir }}/executable`. Your `compile.sh` is also required to
produce its output at `{{ workspace_dir }}/executable` (see the build
contract below), so **the moment you run `./compile.sh`, your build will
overwrite the reference and you will lose the ability to compare**.

To preserve the reference under a stable, tool-agnostic name, run this
**before** you do anything else — before you `ls`, before you read the
docs, before any shell command that might shadow the file:

```bash
[ -e {{ binary_path }} ] || mv {{ workspace_dir }}/executable {{ binary_path }}
```

After this, `{{ binary_path }}` is the reference for the rest of the
run, and `{{ workspace_dir }}/executable` is reserved for your own build
output. Every reference to `{{ binary_path }}` in the rest of these
instructions assumes you have run Step 0. The Stop hook
(`check_reference_diffs.sh`) also expects the reference at this exact
path; if you skip Step 0, the hook silently no-ops and the hidden test
suite becomes your only feedback signal.

